# Interaction-Level Alignment

*A foundational layer for preserving correction in human–AI interaction*

---

## Origin

This concept emerged from examining failure modes in AI interaction, particularly:

- amplification of coherent but untested ideas  
- loss of correction through reinforcement  
- stabilized incoherence in human–AI loops  

It builds on the principle that:

> correctness is less reliable than correctability

---

## Definition

> Interaction-level alignment is the preservation of correction capacity within human–AI interaction

It does not require:

- perfect outputs  
- shared values  
- complete system alignment  

It requires:

> ongoing ability to question, revise, and redirect

---

## Distinction from Other Alignment Layers

### System-Level Alignment
- training, objectives, architecture  
- “Did we build it right?”

### Behavioral Alignment
- outputs, policies, constraints  
- “Does it behave acceptably?”

### Interaction-Level Alignment
- dynamics of conversation  
- user cognition and response  
- “Can errors still be corrected?”

---

## Core Mechanism

Interaction-level alignment depends on:

- oscillation (movement between modes)  
- reversal (reintroduction of missing modes)  
- preserved friction (space for contradiction)  

---

## Failure Condition

> Stabilized incoherence

- coherent  
- stable  
- reinforced  
- not corrected  

This occurs when:

> amplification exceeds correction capacity

---

## Success Condition

> Continuous correctability

- ideas remain revisable  
- contradiction is possible  
- modes can shift  
- interaction remains open  

---

## Key Principle

> Alignment is not correctness—it is the ability to correct

---

## Practical Implication

Even imperfect systems can produce safe outcomes if:

> the interaction preserves correction

Conversely:

> even well-designed systems can fail if interaction suppresses correction

---

## Scope

This layer operates:

- in real-time interaction  
- at the level of cognition and dialogue  
- across humans, AI, and hybrid systems  

It does not:

- guarantee truth  
- replace system-level alignment  
- eliminate risk  

---

## Summary

Interaction-level alignment addresses the earliest failure point:

> loss of correction within the interaction loop

Its role is to:

> preserve oscillation, reversibility, and openness to contradiction
